    <methods>
      <methodStep>
        <description>
          <para>Soil was collected at 10 cm depth. Wet weight was the weight of the soil immediately following collection. Dry weight was the weight of the air-dried soil. Percent moisture content was calculated as ((wet weight - dry weight)/dry weight) * 100. Bulk density was calculated as the dry weight/432 and was in units of g/ml. The soil volume collected was 432 ml. Soil was then fractionated and the following tests were performed on the &lt;2mm portions. The &gt;2mm portions were weighed and stored. pH was measured initially using a 1:2.5 ratio (10g soil to 25ml distilled water). pH was measured again on some samples (10g) using a paste method. In order to calculate percent hygroscopic moisture, a few grams of soil were placed in a 105 degrees Celsius oven for 15 hrs. These samples were weighed prior to and after this drying procedure. The Walkley-Black procedure was used to determine oxidizable organic carbon. That number was then multiplied by 1.724 to get oxidizable organic matter. The values for oxidizable organic carbon and oxidizable organic matter were multiplied by 1.30 to obtain total organic carbon and total organic matter, respectively.</para>
          <para>https://portal.lternet.edu/nis/mapbrowse?scope=knb-lter-nwt&amp;identifier=404</para>
          <para>https://portal.lternet.edu/nis/mapbrowse?scope=knb-lter-nwt&amp;identifier=40</para>
          <para>https://portal.lternet.edu/nis/mapbrowse?scope=knb-lter-nwt&amp;identifier=99</para>
          <para>https://portal.lternet.edu/nis/mapbrowse?scope=knb-lter-nwt&amp;identifier=86</para>
          <para>No samples were collected at saddle grid points 1, 13, 30A, 41, 42, 63, and 71; these are unvegetated “rock” points.</para>
        </description>
      </methodStep>
    </methods>
